'''''EuroTrump''''' is a 90-minute long documentary, which follows [[Geert Wilders]]' campaign for Prime Minister of the Netherlands during the [[Dutch general election, 2017]] and compares him to the U.S. president [[Donald Trump]]. It was directed by [[Stephen Robert Morse]] and [[Nick Hampson]], and co-written by Morse and [[Maria Spinger]]. 

== Background and production ==
Geert Wilders, a right-wing politician in the [[Netherlands]], decided to run for [[Prime Minister]] of the [[Netherlands]] in the [[Dutch general election, 2017]]. Stephen Robert Morse was fascinated by this, particularly after American politician [[Donald Trump]]'s successful presidential election and the [[United Kingdom]] leaving the [[European Union]]. He, along with Nick Hampson and Maria Springer, decided to make a documentary which follows Wilders campaign, and compares him to Donald Trump.<ref name="sbs">{{cite web|url=https://www.sbs.ox.ac.uk/news/eurotrump-documentary-mba-alumni-airs-tv|title=EuroTrump documentary by MBA alumni airs on TV|work=Oxford University Saïd Business School|date=June 29, 2018|accessdate=October 5, 2018}}</ref> "Wilders’ was the first big election in the world after Trump, which is what drew us to the project in the first place. We wanted to make a movie about an election that involved an outsider, someone from the traditional right wing," Hampson said.<ref name="observer">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Kelsey |title='EUROTRUMP' Documentary Provides Inside Look at Geert Wilders |url=https://observer.com/2017/10/documentary-eurotrump-provides-inside-look-at-geert-wilders/ |accessdate=5 October 2018 |work=[[The New York Observer]] |publisher=Joseph Meyer |date=November 24, 2017}}</ref> [[Stephen Robert Morse]] and [[Nick Hampson]] co-directed the documentary, and [[Maria Spinger]] co-wrote it. The soundtrack was composed by Harry Davidson, a music scholar from the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name="sbs"/>

The filming began in December 2016, a couple of days after a trial where Wilders was convicted of hate speech, which concluded with the judge, Hendrik Steenhuis, deciding that the court would not impose any punishment on Wilders following the trial.<ref name="newsweek">{{cite news |last1=Persio |first1=Sofia Lotto |title=Is Geert Wilders Really The Dutch Donald? 'EuroTrump' Follow Anti-Islam Politician to Find Out |url=https://www.newsweek.com/eurotrump-978913 |accessdate=5 October 2018 |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=June 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lowe |first1=Josh |title=Dutch Far-Right Politician Geert Wilders Convicted of Hate Speech |url=https://www.newsweek.com/geert-wilders-trial-convicted-hate-speech-moroccans-530025 |accessdate=1 November 2018 |work=Newsweek |date=December 9, 2016}}</ref> The makers of the documentary wanted to learn the details of Wilders' viewpoint and engage it, despite disagreeing with his ideas. The Dutch press were not supportive of the documentary; however, Morse stated, "I think that’s an ignorant approach. You should try understand the people who disagree with. If you don't have an in-depth understanding of someone it makes it very challenging to understand their viewpoint, if you don't understand where those views came from."<ref name="newsweek"/> Morse stated that throughout the whole production time span, the production team applied the lessons they learned at the [[Saïd Business School]].<ref name="sbs"/> Morse thought that even though Wilders' had such strong beliefs politically,  he was a likeable person; at their first meeting for the documentary, Wilders' and Morse made each other laugh often, despite Morse expecting Wilders' to be "a monster."<ref name="observer"/>

The documentary follows Wilders' campaign and provides an up-close view of him, discussing what his ideas are politically, including clearing Islam from the [[Netherlands]] and shutting down all [[mosques]],<ref name="observer"/> as well as providing information about himself, such as talking about his two cats and describing himself as a "spoilt child."<ref name="newsweek"/> The documentary also discusses how Wilders' constantly has strict security around him, and how it affects him.<ref name="observer"/> Morse describes the comparison between Wilders and Trump as ironic, due to how little they have in common.<ref name="newsweek"/> Morse thought that his work producing ''[[Amanda Knox]]'' allowed Wilders to trust him more; many journalists would have a much more difficult time getting up-close to Wilders.<ref name="sbs"/> The show premiered on [[Hulu]] in June 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cohn |first1=Gabe |title=What’s on TV Monday: ‘The Rape of Recy Taylor’ and ‘Strangers’ |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/02/arts/television/whats-on-tv-monday-the-rape-of-recy-taylor-and-strangers.html |accessdate=5 October 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[A.G. Sulzberger]] |date=July 2, 2018}}</ref>

